    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Just a Moral Lapse, or an Impeachable Offense?; Excusing Perjury</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Geraldyn Eckber letter on Sept 16 editorial recalls Kenneth W Starr excused Monica Lewinsky's perjury in Paula Jones case in what she sees as inappropriate probe of Pres Clinton; drawing (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Lying under oath (editorial, Sept. 16) is a criminal offense unless, apparently, a prosecutor can use that perjury to his advantage.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Lying under oath (editorial, Sept. 16) is a criminal offense unless, apparently, a prosecutor can use that perjury to his advantage.</p>
        <p>So Kenneth W. Starr excused Monica S. Lewinsky's perjury in the Paula Jones case by giving her immunity to get her to testify against Bill Clinton.</p>
        <p>It seems that perjury doesn't count if it lands you a bigger fish when you're fishing for a reason to hook the President, delving into waters that had nothing to do with his official business.</p>
        <p>GERALDYN ECKBER  Fairfield, Conn., Sept. 16, 1998</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
